Definition 0.1. Let $R$ be a noetherian, commutative ring, and ${\mathscr{S}}$ an $R$–linear triangulated category. In this article an $R$–linear homological functor $H:{\mathscr{S}}\longrightarrow R\text{--\rm Mod}$ will be called locally finite if $H^{i}(s)$ is a finite $R$–module for all $s\in{\mathscr{S}}$ and $i\in{\mathbb{Z}}$, and if, for any fixed object $s\in{\mathscr{S}}$, we have $H^{i}(s)=0$ for $i\ll 0$. The functor $H$ is called finite if it is locally finite, and in addition $H^{i}(s)=0$ for $i\gg 0$.
Definition 4.2. A powerful ${\langle G\rangle}_{n}$–approximating sequence is an inverse system $\cdots\longrightarrow E_{3}\longrightarrow E_{2}\longrightarrow E_{1}% \longrightarrow E_{0}$ in ${\mathscr{T}}$, so that (i) Each $E_{m}$ belongs to ${\langle G\rangle}_{n}$. (ii) The map ${\mathscr{H}}^{i}(E_{m+1})\longrightarrow{\mathscr{H}}^{i}(E_{m})$ is an isomorphism whenever $i\geq-m$. Suppose we are also given an object $F\in{\mathscr{T}}$, together with (iii) A map from $F$ to the approximating system $E_{*}$. (iv) The map in (iii) is such that ${\mathscr{H}}^{i}(F)\longrightarrow{\mathscr{H}}^{i}(E_{m})$ is an isomorphism whenever $i\geq-m$. Then we declare $E_{*}$ to be a powerful ${\langle G\rangle}_{n}$–approximating system for $F$.
Definition 2.2. Let $\alpha:\mathscr{C}\to\mathscr{P}$ be a twisting morphism. (1) Two $\infty_{\alpha}$-morphisms $A\rightsquigarrow A^{\prime}$ of $\mathscr{P}$-algebras are homotopic (as $\infty_{\alpha}$-morphisms) if they are homotopic seen as morphisms of $\mathscr{C}$-coalgebras $\mathrm{B}_{\alpha}A\to\mathrm{B}_{\alpha}A^{\prime}$. (2) Dually, two $\infty_{\alpha}$-morphisms $C^{\prime}\rightsquigarrow C$ of $\mathscr{C}$-coalgebras are homotopic (as $\infty_{\alpha}$-morphisms) if they are homotopic seen as morphisms of $\mathscr{P}$-algebras $\Omega_{\alpha}C^{\prime}\to\Omega_{\alpha}C$.
Definition 2.7. Let $\alpha:\mathscr{C}\to\mathscr{P}$ be a twisting morphism. (1) Let $A,A^{\prime}$ be two $\mathscr{P}$-algebras. The deformation complex of $\infty_{\alpha}$-morphisms of $\mathscr{P}$-algebras from $A$ to $A^{\prime}$ is the $\mathcal{s}\mathscr{L}_{\infty}$-algebra $\hom^{\alpha}(\mathrm{B}_{\alpha}A,A^{\prime})$. (2) Let $C^{\prime},C$ be two $\mathscr{C}$-coalgebras. The deformation complex of $\infty_{\alpha}$-morphisms of $\mathscr{C}$-coalgebras from $C^{\prime}$ to $C$ is the $\mathcal{s}\mathscr{L}_{\infty}$-algebra $\hom^{\alpha}(C^{\prime},\Omega_{\alpha}C)$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathscr{C}$ be a cooperad, let $\mathscr{P}$ be an operad, and let $\alpha:\mathscr{C}\to\mathscr{P}$ be a twisting morphism. (1) Let $A,A^{\prime}$ be two $\mathscr{P}$-algebras. An $\infty$-morphism $\Psi$ of $\mathscr{P}$-algebras relative to $\alpha$ — or and $\infty_{\alpha}$-morphism — from $A$ to $A^{\prime}$ is a morphism $\Psi:\mathrm{B}_{\alpha}A\longrightarrow\mathrm{B}_{\alpha}A^{\prime}$ of $\mathscr{C}$-coalgebras. We also write $\Psi:A\rightsquigarrow A^{\prime}$. (2) Let $C^{\prime},C$ be two $\mathscr{C}$-coalgebras. An $\infty$-morphism $\Phi$ of $\mathscr{C}$-coalgebras relative to $\alpha$ — or and $\infty_{\alpha}$-morphism — from $C^{\prime}$ to $C$ is a morphism $\Psi:\Omega_{\alpha}C^{\prime}\longrightarrow\Omega_{\alpha}C$ of $\mathscr{P}$-algebras. We also write $\Phi:C^{\prime}\rightsquigarrow C$.
Definition 18. Let $X$ be a set. We define ZSDDs over $X$ and the interpretation $\xi_{X}$ inductively as follows. • $\bot$ and $\varepsilon$ are ZSDDs, and interpreted by $\emptyset$ and $\{\varepsilon\}$, respectively. • $x$ and $\pm x$ are ZSDDs for each $x\in X$, and interpreted by $\{\{x\}\}$ and $\{\varepsilon,\{x\}\}$, respectively. • If $p_{i},s_{i}$ are ZSDDs for $1\leq i\leq n$, then $\{(p_{1},s_{1}),\dots,(p_{n},s_{n})\}$ is a ZSDD, and interpreted by $\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}(\xi_{X}(p_{i})\sqcup\xi_{X}(s_{i}))$, where $\sqcup$ is defined by $P\sqcup Q=\{A\cup B\mid A\in P,B\in Q\}.$
Definition 26. Let $\alpha\in\mathcal{S}(X)$ be an SDD. 1. $\alpha$ is strongly deterministic if every decomposition of $\alpha$ has pairwise disjoint primes. More concretely, every decomposition $\{(p_{i},s_{i})\}_{i=1}^{n}$ in $\alpha$ satisfies $\sigma(p_{i})\cap\sigma(p_{j})=\emptyset$ whenever $i\neq j$. (A decomposition of a Boolean function having this property is said to be strongly deterministic [10].) 2. $\alpha$ is a partition SDD if it is strongly deterministic and every decomposition $\{(p_{i},s_{i})\}_{i=1}^{n}$ in $\alpha$ satisfies $\sigma(p_{1})\cup\dots\cup\sigma(p_{n})=\mathcal{P}(X)$.
Definition 12. Let $(X,\leq)$ be a totally ordered set. $F\in\mathcal{D}(X)$ is said to respect $\leq$ if, for all $x,y\in X$, $x<y$ holds whenever $y$ occurs as a descendant of $x$ in $F$.
Definition 21. We define an SDD or a ZSDD respecting $v$ inductively as follows. 1. $\top$, $\bot$, $\varepsilon$ respect any vtree. 2. $x$, $\neg x$, $\pm x$ respect a leaf corresponding to $x$. 3. If $\alpha$ respects either $v$ or $w$, then $\alpha$ respects $(v,w)$. 4. If $p_{i}$ respects $v$ and $s_{i}$ respects $w$ for each $1\leq i\leq n$, then $\{(p_{1},s_{1}),\dots,(p_{n},s_{n})\}$ respects $(v,w)$.
Definition 6. A diagram over a set $X$ is a rooted, directed acyclic graph with labeled nodes and edges satisfying the following. • There are two types of nodes: decision nodes and terminal nodes. • Each decision node is labeled by an element of $X$, and has two outgoing edges. One of the edges is labeled by $0$ and another is labeled by $1$, and called a $0$-edge and a $1$-edge, respectively. • Each terminal node is labeled by either $0$ or $1$, and has no outgoing edges. A terminal node is called either a $0$-terminal node or a $1$-terminal node according to its label. We write $\mathcal{D}(X)$ for the set of all diagrams over a set $X$.
Definition 17. Let $X$ be a set. We define SDDs over $X$ and the interpretation $\sigma_{X}$ inductively as follows. • $\top$ and $\bot$ are SDDs, and interpreted by $\mathcal{P}(X)$ and $\emptyset$, respectively. • $x$ and $\neg x$ are SDDs for each $x\in X$, and interpreted by $\{C\subseteq X\mid x\in C\}$ and $\{C\subseteq X\mid x\notin C\}$, respectively. • If $p_{i},s_{i}$ are SDDs for $1\leq i\leq n$, then $\{(p_{1},s_{1}),\dots,(p_{n},s_{n})\}$ is an SDD, and interpreted by $\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}(\sigma_{X}(p_{i})\cap\sigma_{X}(s_{i}))$. An SDD of either the first or the second form is called a terminal, and the third a decomposition. We regard a decomposition as a set of pairs, and thus the order of pairs is irrelevant.
Definition 1. Let $X$ be a set. A combination over $X$ is just a subset of $X$, and a combination set over $X$ is a set of combinations over $X$. In other words, a combination and a combination set are elements of $\mathcal{P}(X)$ and $\mathcal{P}^{2}(X)$, respectively.
Definition 3. Let $X$ be a set. A Boolean function over $X$ is an element of $2^{2^{X}}$, where $2=\{0,1\}$.
Definition 22. Let $v$ and $w$ be vtrees. We define embeddings (of vtrees) from $v$ to $w$ inductively. Let $f\colon|v|\to|w|$ be a map. • $f$ is an embedding if $v$ is a leaf. • $f$ is an embedding if $w=(w_{1},w_{2})$, and $f$ is an embedding from $v$ to either $w_{1}$ or $w_{2}$. • $f$ is an embedding if $v=(v_{1},v_{2})$, $w=(w_{1},w_{2})$, and the restriction of $f$ to $|v_{i}|$ is an embedding from $v_{i}$ to $w_{i}$ for $i=1,2$.
Definition 9. Given a set $X$, the interpretation $\zeta_{X}\colon\mathcal{D}(X)\to\mathcal{P}^{2}(X)$ of a diagram as a ZDD is defined as follows: $\displaystyle\zeta_{X}(\mathbf{0})$ $\displaystyle=\emptyset,\qquad\zeta_{X}(\mathbf{1})=\{\varepsilon\},$ $\displaystyle\zeta_{X}((a,F,G))$ $\displaystyle=\zeta_{X}(F)\cup\{A\cup\{a\}\mid A\in\zeta_{X}(G)\}.$
Definition 7. Given a set $X$, the interpretation $\beta_{X}\colon\mathcal{D}(X)\to\mathcal{P}^{2}(X)$ of a diagram as a BDD is defined as follows: $\displaystyle\beta_{X}(\mathbf{0})$ $\displaystyle=\emptyset,\qquad\beta_{X}(\mathbf{1})=\mathcal{P}(X),$ $\displaystyle\beta_{X}((a,F,G))$ $\displaystyle=\{C\in\beta(F)\mid a\notin C\}\cup\{C\in\beta(G)\mid a\in C\}.$
Definition 20. A vtree for a set $X$ is a rooted, full binary tree whose leaves are in one-to-one correspondence with elements of $X$.
Definition 16. Let $X$ and $Y$ be disjoint sets of variables, and $f$ a Boolean function over $X\cup Y$. An $(X,Y)$-decomposition of $f$ is a representation of $f$ by a Boolean formula of the form $f(X,Y)=\bigvee_{i=1}^{n}(p_{i}(X)\land s_{i}(Y))$, where $p_{i}$ and $s_{i}$ depend only on variables in $X$ and $Y$, respectively. Each $p_{i}$ is called a prime, and each $s_{i}$ is called a sub of the decomposition.
Definition 27. A ZSDD $\alpha\in\mathcal{Z}(X)$ is strongly deterministic if every decomposition of $\alpha$ has pairwise disjoint primes.
Definition 2.18. A $(J,J^{\prime})$-perversity is a map of posets $U\colon J\to\mathcal{O}(J^{\prime})^{\textnormal{op}}$ such that $U_{j}+1\subseteq U_{j-1}$ for any $j$ in $J$. The set $\mathrm{Perv}(J,J^{\prime})$ of all $(J,J^{\prime})$-perversities inherits a poset structure from the inclusion in $\textnormal{Pos}(J,\mathcal{O}(J^{\prime})^{\textnormal{op}})^{\textnormal{op}}$. It is a $\mathbb{Z}$-poset with $1$ acting as $U\mapsto U\dotplus(-1)$.
Definition 2.22. A perversity function (on $\mathbb{Z}$) is a function $p\colon\mathbb{Z}\to\mathbb{Z}$ such that $p(n)\leq p(n+1)\leq p(n)+1,$ for every $n\in\mathbb{Z}$. It is called a strict perversity function if $p(n+2)-1\leq p(n)\leq p(n+1)\leq p(n)+1,$ for every $n\in\mathbb{Z}$. The set $\mathrm{perv}_{\mathbb{Z}}$ of perversity functions is a poset with the partial order induced by the inclusion $\mathrm{perv}_{\mathbb{Z}}\subseteq\textnormal{Pos}(\mathbb{Z},\mathbb{Z})$. It is a $\mathbb{Z}$-poset with the action $(p\dotplus 1)(n)=p(n+1)$.
Definition 2.12. Let $J_{1}$ and $J_{2}$ be $\mathbb{Z}$-tosets. A Bridgeland $J_{1}\times_{\textnormal{lex}}J_{2}$-slicing $\mathfrak{t}$ of $\mathscr{D}$ is said to be gluable if it is $e$-compatible, where $e\colon J_{1}\times J_{2}\to J_{2}\times J_{1}$ is the exchange map.
Definition 2.37. Let $\mathfrak{t}$ be a bounded t-structure on $\mathscr{D}$. An abelian $\mathbb{Z}$-slicing $\hat{\mathfrak{t}}$ on $\heartsuit_{\mathfrak{t}}$ is called: • perverse (or weak grading) if $\heartsuit_{\mathfrak{t};\phi}\boxslash\heartsuit_{\mathfrak{t};\psi}[n]$ for $\phi>\psi+n$; • grading (or radical) if $\heartsuit_{\mathfrak{t};\phi}\boxslash\heartsuit_{\mathfrak{t};\psi}[n]$ for $\phi>\psi+n$ and for $\phi=\psi+n$ with $n\geq 2$; • gluable if $\heartsuit_{\mathfrak{t};\phi}\boxslash\heartsuit_{\mathfrak{t};\psi}[n]$ for $\phi>\psi$ and $n>0$;
